        <h2 class="main-content__title--base col-s__1 col-e__11 row-s__1 row-e__2">HTML Tutorial
        </h2>

        <p class="main-content__text--base col-s__2 col-e__10">
            HyperText Markup Language (HTML) is the standard markup
                    language for web pages. "HyperText" refers to the hyperlinks
                    contained in a HTML webpage, and "Markup Language" refers to
                    HTML's use of tags to define the layout and elements of a
                    web page.
        </p>



    </section>

    <section class="grid-container main-content__grid-container--base">

        <h2 class="main-content__title--base col-s__1 col-e__11 row-s__1 row-e__2">Tag Breakdown</h2>

        <p class="main-content__text--base col-s__2 col-e__10">
            A <strong>tag</strong> is a generic term used for language
                    element descriptor. HTML tags are usually defined as "a set"
                    of characters constituting a formatted command for a web
                    page".
                    Most tags must have two parts. The first part is the <b>Opening
                        tag</b>,
                    consisting of an element name within angle brackets (<span>&#60;</span><span>&#62;</span>),
                    signifying
                    the start of an element. The second part is the <b>closing
                        tag</b>,
                    consisting of the same structure as the opening tag, but
                    with a forward-slash (/)
                    before the element name. However, There are some tags
                    that dont require a
                    closing tag (i.e. images). When used in an HTML
                    document, tags form
                    the building blocks for HTML <strong>elements</strong>.
                    An HTML element
                    tells the browser what content to display and how to
                    display it.
        </p>

        <figure class="main-content__reference-image col-s__2 col-e__9">
            <img src="images/tag-breakdown-reference.png"
                        alt="A reference image to the anatomy of an HTML tag">
                        <figcaption class="page-description__reference-imagecaption">Anatomy of an HTML tag</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p class="main-content__text--base col-s__2 col-e__10">
            Attributes define additional properties of an element such as an input type, a links value reference, or
            the width and height of an image. Attributes are always specified within the opening tag of an element and 
            consist of the attributes name and it's value enclosed within quotation marks (name="value").
        </p>
    </section>


    <section class="grid-container main-content__grid-container--base">

        <h2 class="main-content__title--base col-s__1 col-e__11 row-s__1 row-e__2">Most common tags
        </h2>

        <p class="main-content__text--base col-s__2 col-e__10 row-s__2 row-e__3">
            There are too many elements to list, but the elements
                    outlined below are most commonly used
                    in web development:
        </p>


    <ul class="main-content__text--base col-s__2 col-e__11 row-s__3 row-e__4">
        <li>
            <span>&#60;</span>p<span>&#62;</span>: Defines a
            text paragraph. Browsers automatically add a
            whitespace before
            and after a paragraph.
        </li>
        <li>
            <span>&#60;</span>h1<span>&#62;</span>, <span>&#60;</span>h2<span>&#62;</span>,
            <span>&#60;</span>h...<span>&#62;</span>, <span>&#60;</span>h6<span>&#62;</span>:
            Defines a title text.
        </li>
        <li>
            <span>&#60;</span>a<span>&#62;</span>: Defines a
            link. The element between the opening and closing tags can be clicked on to refer 
            the user to another page.
        </li>

        <li>
            <span>&#60;</span>b<span>&#62;</span>: Declares that a text should be <b>bold</b>.
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <span>&#60;</span>strong<span>&#62;</span>: Declares a <strong>bold</strong> with emphasys.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>

        <li>
            <span>&#60;</span>img<span>&#62;</span>: Defines an image to be displayed on the page.
        </li>

        <li>
            <span>&#60;</span>ol<span>&#62;</span>, <span>&#60;</span>ul<span>&#62;</span>: 
            Define a list of elements thats either ordered or unordered.
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <span>&#60;</span>li<span>&#62;</span>: Define used by lists to define a list item.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    </section>


<section class="grid-container main-content__grid-container--base">

    <h2 class="main-content__title--base col-s__1 col-e__11 row-s__1 row-e__2">Basic HTML Document
    </h2>

    <p class="main-content__text--base col-s__2 col-e__10 row-s__2 row-e__3">
        HTML documents contain a specific syntax that tells a
        browser that its an
        HTML document, allowing it to correctly process it's
        content. Below shows
        the basic structure of a modern HTML document.
    </p>

    <ol class="main-content__text--base col-s__2 col-e__7 row-s__3 row-e__4">
        <li><p>
            The <span>&#60;</span>!DOCTYPE html<span>&#62;</span>
            declaraction describes in what version of HTML
            the document is written to allow
            a browser to interpret the text correctly. This
            should always be at the start of your
            document.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
            The <span>&#60;</span>html<span>&#62;</span> and
            <span>&#47;&#60;</span>html<span>&#62;</span>
            tags are the root of a web page and tells the
            browser that it is reading HTML code.
            All other contents of your page are between
            these tags.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
            The <span>&#60;</span>head<span>&#62;</span> and
            <span>&#47;&#60;</span>head<span>&#62;</span>
            tags contain information about the web page such
            as title, meta tags and the location of the
            CSS file. Most of this information is of little
            use to a website visitor and is not directly
            visible to them.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
            The <span>&#60;</span>meta<span>&#62;</span>
            element defines metadata (information about
            data) about an HTML document. They are typically
            used
            to specify character sets, page descriptions,
            keywords, etc. Metadata is used by browsers to
            help disply contents,
            search engines for page keywords, and many other
            services.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
            The <span>&#60;</span>title<span>&#62;</span>
            element declares a pages title to a browser to
            display at the top of the browser window.
        </li>
        <li><p>
            The <span>&#60;</span>body<span>&#62;</span> and
            <span>&#47;&#60;</span>body<span>&#62;</span>
            tags contain all content that's viewable on the
            browser such as headings, paragraphs,
            hyperlinks, images tables, etc. For example, all
            contents within the white part of this page is
            within the body.
        </p></li>
    </ol>

